alarmSubsysSourceDescr.name: alarmSubsysSourceDescr
alarmSubsysSourceDescr.description: A description of the source generating the trap for the Alarm Condition. Used in alarmSubSystemTrap to describe the alarm source. Example: 'batteryVoltageDescription'

alarmSubsysStatusOid.name: alarmSubsysStatusOid
alarmSubsysStatusOid.description: The OID (name) of the object indicating the alarm-status for which the alarm is generated. The Status must be an INTEGER type. Example: SP2-MIB::batteryVoltage.batteryVoltageStatus 1.3.6.1.4.1.12148.10.3.5.2: This object maybe polled by the SNMP management application, to monitor the current Status object.

alarmSubsysStatusValue.name: alarmSubsysStatusValue
alarmSubsysStatusValue.description: The value of the Status object of the subsystem for which the alarm-status is generated. The OID (name) of this object is indicated by alarmSubsysStatusOid above. Example: the value of SP2-MIB::batteryVoltage.batteryVoltageStatus one of: error (0), normal (1), minorAlarm (2), etc.

alarmSubsysStatusOnOff.name: alarmSubsysStatusOnOff
alarmSubsysStatusOnOff.description: This indicates if the abnormal condition is on or goes off.

alarmMeasuredVarOid.name: alarmMeasuredVarOid
alarmMeasuredVarOid.description: The OID (name) of the measured-object indicating some measurement (e.g voltage) for which the alarm is generated. Example: SP2-MIB::batteryVoltage.batteryVoltageValue 1.3.6.1.4.1.12148.10.3.5.1 This object maybe polled by the SNMP management application, to monitor the current measurement.

alarmMeasuredVarValue.name: alarmMeasuredVarValue
alarmMeasuredVarValue.description: The value of the measured-object for which the alarm-status is generated, for example 13 volt. The actual value is in units defined by the actual variable (e.g volts). The units must use INTEGER type. The OID (name) of this object is indicated by alarmMeasuredVarOid above. Example: Value of SP2-MIB::batteryVoltage.batteryVoltageValue 'The measured battery voltage'

powerSystemLongitude.name: powerSystemLongitude
powerSystemLongitude.description: A part of the systems global positioning data. The range +-180degrees Longitude lines are imaginary lines running from the north pole to the south pole. Longitudes are usually (WGS84) referenced from Greenwich, England where it has been established as Zero Degrees longitude. Latitude and Longitude together with the Elevation can be used for automagically placing system icons on NMS/Sitemonitors system that support this.

powerSystemLongitudeDecimal.name: powerSystemLongitudeDecimal
powerSystemLongitudeDecimal.description: The decimal part of dcSystemLatitude contains up to 7digits. This number is in 1/1000000 degree fractions or 0,0000001 degree. A part of the systems global positioning data. Longitude lines are imaginary lines running from the north pole to the south pole. Longitudes are usually (WGS84) referenced from Greenwich, England where it has been established as Zero Degrees longitude. Latitude and Longitude together with the Elevation can be used for automagically placing system icons on NMS/Sitemonitors system that support this.

powerSystemLatitude.name: powerSystemLatitude
powerSystemLatitude.description: A part of the systems global positioning data. The latitude gives the location of a place on Earth (or other planetary body) north or south of the equator. Lines of Latitude has a range of +-90 degrees and are the imaginary horizontal lines shown running east-to-west (or west to east). Latitude and Longitude together with the Elevation can be used for automagically placing system icons on NMS/Sitemonitors system that support this.

powerSystemLatitudeDecimal.name: powerSystemLatitudeDecimal
powerSystemLatitudeDecimal.description: The decimal part of dcSystemLatitude contains up to 7digits. This number is in 1/1000000 degree fractions or 0,0000001 degree. A part of the systems global positioning data. Lines of Latitude has a range of +-90 degrees and are the imaginary horizontal lines shown running east-to-west (or west to east). Latitude and Longitude together with the Elevation can be used for automagically placing system icons on NMS/Sitemonitors system that support this. Longitude lines are imaginary lines running from the north pole to the south pole. Longitudes are usually (WGS84) referenced from Greenwich, England where it has been established as Zero Degrees longitude. Latitude and Longitude together with the Elevation can be used for automagically placing system icons on NMS/Sitemonitors system that support this.

powerSystemElevation.name: powerSystemElevation
